Hello!
Why do you take a custom template from the arguments, but render the template from the settings anyway?

```python
class CaptchaTextInput(BaseCaptchaTextInput):
    def __init__(self, attrs=None, **kwargs):
        self._args = kwargs
        self._args['field_template'] = self._args.get('field_template') or settings.CAPTCHA_FIELD_TEMPLATE

    def format_output(self, rendered_widgets):
        hidden_field, text_field = rendered_widgets

        if self._args['output_format']:
            return self._args['output_format'] % {...}

        elif self._args['field_template']:
            context = {
                'image': mark_safe(self.image_and_audio),
                'hidden_field': mark_safe(self.hidden_field),
                'text_field': mark_safe(self.text_field)
            }
            return render_to_string(settings.CAPTCHA_FIELD_TEMPLATE, context)    # <---- This line
```

Hello, 
I have been trying to connect to the user_socket but I've been getting APIErrors. I was wondering if this is an issue with Binance. The exact message I have been receiving is: {binance.exceptions.BinanceAPIException: APIError(code=-1000): An unknown error occured while processing the request.} 
I have used the exact same code without any issues before and this is the first time I've seen this

Flask restplus version: 0.9.2

The documentation here : http://flask-restplus.readthedocs.io/en/stable/errors.html specifies that you can also "override the default error handler when used wihtout parameter" doing something like this:
```python
@api.errorhandler
def default_error_handler(error):
    '''Default error handler'''
    return {'message': str(error)}, getattr(error, 'code', 500)
```
If I want to return a reponse a little bit more detailed like this: 
```python
@api.errorhandler
def default_handler(e):
    return { "errors": [{"code": "something unexpected happened", "message": str(e)}],"meta": { "status": "error" }}
```
This is what is being returned to the client: (I wasn't expecting the message to appear twice in the response)
```json
{
    "errors": [
        {
            "code": "something unexpected happened",
            "message": "name 'purposely_undefined_variable' is not defined"
        }
    ],
    "message": "name 'purposely_undefined_variable' is not defined",
    "meta": {
        "status": "error"
    }
}
```

I was expecting the following response instead:
```json
{
    "errors": [
        {
            "code": "something unexpected happened",
            "message": "name 'purposely_undefined_variable' is not defined"
        }
    ],
    "meta": {
        "status": "error"
    }
}
```
By commenting https://github.com/noirbizarre/flask-restplus/blob/master/flask_restplus/api.py#L589 
this line out, I get the behavior I expected and it doesn't seem to have any side effects.

I was about to submit a PR but I wanted to know if this was intentional or not before doing so?

Thanks,
Thomas

